<subSubSection box="[151,1000,1446,1471]" pageId="24" pageNumber="475" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,1446,2011]" box="[151,1000,1446,1471]" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,299,1446,1471]" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">Type species</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Williams, 1988" authorityName="Williams" authorityYear="1988" box="[313,735,1446,1471]" class="Anthozoa" family="Alcyoniidae" genus="Alcyonium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="24" pageNumber="475" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="distinctum">
<emphasis box="[313,557,1446,1471]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">Alcyonium distinctum</emphasis>
Williams, 1988
</taxonomicName>
by original designation
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="475" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,1446,2011]" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1482,1507]" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Colonies lobate, lobes arising from a short, distinct stalk. Polyps retractile. Sclerites present in stalk surface only, absent from polyps, polyparium surface and colony interior. Sclerites are spheroids or radiates. Colonies vividly colored in life as a result of alcohol-soluble pigments. Sclerites colorless.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="475" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,1446,2011]" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1590,1615]" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Greek 
<emphasis box="[560,674,1590,1615]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">porphyros</emphasis>
meaning purple, and 
<emphasis box="[952,1028,1590,1615]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">phyton</emphasis>
, a creature (plant or animal), in recognition of the vivid purple color of the 
<typeStatus box="[636,684,1627,1651]" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">type</typeStatus>
species. Gender: neutral.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="25" lastPageNumber="476" pageId="24" pageNumber="475" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,1446,2011]" lastBlockId="25.[151,1436,151,213]" lastPageId="25" lastPageNumber="476" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1662,1687]" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">Remarks.</emphasis>
Phylogenetic analyses unite 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mcfadden &amp; Van Ofwegen" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Williams" baseAuthorityYear="1988" box="[647,956,1662,1687]" class="Anthozoa" family="Parasphaerascleridae" genus="Porphyrophyton" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="24" pageNumber="475" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="distinctum" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis box="[647,956,1662,1687]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">Porphyrophyton distinctum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[964,1064,1662,1687]" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">n. comb.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in a clade with other soft corals endemic to 
<collectingCountry box="[284,430,1698,1723]" name="South Africa" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">South Africa</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[446,513,1698,1723]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1614,1636]" captionTargetBox="[171,1407,217,1570]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,195,1590]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Maximum likelihood phylogeny of Octocorallia based on combined, partitioned analysis of 28S rDNA, COI and 16S mtDNA.South African species and clades are identified in blue. Filled circles indicate nodes with&gt;70% bootstrap support and Bayesian posterior probabilities&gt;0.95 (shown for South African clades only). Strongly supported clades (bootstrap 70%) with no South African members have been collapsed to facilitate readability. Phylogenetic position of Protodendron repens indicated with *." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1114481/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), including other species formerly placed in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mcfadden &amp; Van Ofwegen" authorityYear="2017" box="[1026,1146,1698,1723]" class="Anthozoa" family="Alcyoniidae" genus="Alcyonium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="24" pageNumber="475" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1026,1146,1698,1723]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">Alcyonium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Unlike 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">
<taxonomicName authority="Mcfadden &amp; Van Ofwegen, 2017" authorityName="Mcfadden &amp; Van Ofwegen" authorityYear="2017" box="[1245,1365,1698,1723]" class="Anthozoa" family="Alcyoniidae" genus="Alcyonium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="24" pageNumber="475" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus" sensu="stricto" status="sensu stricto">Alcyonium</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="24" pageNumber="475" sensu="stricto">sensu stricto</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(McFadden &amp; Ofwegen 2013), 
<taxonomicName authority="Mcfadden &amp; Van Ofwegen, 2017" authorityName="Mcfadden &amp; Van Ofwegen" authorityYear="2017" box="[588,770,1734,1759]" class="Anthozoa" family="Parasphaerascleridae" genus="Porphyrophyton" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="24" pageNumber="475" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[588,770,1734,1759]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">Porphyrophyton</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[778,857,1734,1759]" pageId="24" pageNumber="475" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[778,857,1734,1759]" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">n. gen.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
completely lacks sclerites in the polyps, surface of the polyparium and interior coenenchyme, and has only spheroids and radiates in the surface of the short stalk. Like most other members of Leptophytidae n. fam., its bright purple color in life is the result of alcohol-soluble pigments rather than permanently pigmented sclerites. The complete lack of sclerites in the polyps, the growth form with lobes arising from a short stalk, and the spheroidal sclerites in the stalk surface are all characters that distinguish 
<taxonomicName authority="Mcfadden &amp; Van Ofwegen, 2017" authorityName="Mcfadden &amp; Van Ofwegen" authorityYear="2017" box="[284,466,1914,1939]" class="Anthozoa" family="Parasphaerascleridae" genus="Porphyrophyton" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="24" pageNumber="475" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[284,466,1914,1939]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">Porphyrophyton</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[478,561,1914,1939]" pageId="24" pageNumber="475" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[478,561,1914,1939]" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">n. gen.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
from the other genera included in Leptophytidae n. fam. Morphologically, 
<taxonomicName authority="Mcfadden &amp; Van Ofwegen, 2017" authorityName="Mcfadden &amp; Van Ofwegen" authorityYear="2017" box="[151,333,1950,1975]" class="Anthozoa" family="Parasphaerascleridae" genus="Porphyrophyton" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="24" pageNumber="475" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[151,333,1950,1975]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">Porphyrophyton</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[343,425,1950,1975]" pageId="24" pageNumber="475" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[343,425,1950,1975]" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">n. gen.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
most closely resembles some species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="McFadden &amp; van Ofwegen" authorityYear="2013" box="[906,1121,1950,1975]" class="Anthozoa" family="Parasphaerascleridae" genus="Parasphaerasclera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="24" pageNumber="475" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[906,1121,1950,1975]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="475">Parasphaerasclera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="" authorityYear="2013" box="[1138,1377,1950,1975]" class="Anthozoa" family="Parasphaerascleridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="24" pageNumber="475" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="family">Parasphaerascleridae</taxonomicName>
) that likewise have no sclerites in the polyps and have only spheroids or radiates in the colony surface. That genus, however, has permanently pigmented sclerites as well as sclerites in the colony interior (McFadden &amp; Ofwegen 2013), and is phylogenetically distant from Leptophytidae n. fam. (
<figureCitation box="[903,968,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1614,1636]" captionTargetBox="[171,1407,217,1570]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,195,1590]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Maximum likelihood phylogeny of Octocorallia based on combined, partitioned analysis of 28S rDNA, COI and 16S mtDNA.South African species and clades are identified in blue. Filled circles indicate nodes with&gt;70% bootstrap support and Bayesian posterior probabilities&gt;0.95 (shown for South African clades only). Strongly supported clades (bootstrap 70%) with no South African members have been collapsed to facilitate readability. Phylogenetic position of Protodendron repens indicated with *." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1114481/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="476">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
